# Requirements
- Follow the target distribution plan using the provided counts as planning targets.
- The fluctuation logic has already been handled upstream, so do not re-interpret the plan or re-sample a new distribution.
- Minor local deviation is acceptable only when needed to avoid obviously repetitive or incoherent questions.
- Write question text so it can stand on its own when the evaluation system supplies context separately.
- Do not cite turn IDs, session IDs, or hidden-history hints inside the question text.
- Do not write wording such as `considering D1:6 and D1:8`, `as seen in Session 1`, or `based on D2:4`.
- Avoid unresolved deictic wording such as `this`, `that`, `the two`, or `those earlier issues` when the referent is outside the quoted anchor text. Rewrite the referent explicitly.
- In longer conversations, do not spread long-term questions evenly just because there are more turns. Prefer to place the strongest trajectory, repair, growth, and generalization questions in later sessions where enough history has accumulated.
- In earlier sessions, prioritize control items such as instant emotion, near-term fact, and early pattern-establishment questions.
- Extra question budget in longer conversations should come from genuinely new memory signals, not from multiple rephrasings of the same relational shift.
- Do not generate multiple questions that all test the same closure signal, such as repeated goodbyes, thank-you exchanges, or increasingly relaxed sign-offs, unless they clearly probe different underlying inferences.
- Keep retrieval questions selective. Prefer facts that matter for later emotional interpretation or long-term memory, not every local factual detail.
- Prioritize long-term implicit emotion items.
- Include factual control items and instant emotion control items.
- Include a smaller set of diagnostic and robustness items.
- For adversarial items, use one of:
  - pseudo_relevant_history
  - insufficient_evidence
  - pseudo_conflict
- The blueprint assumes the full conversation is available. If you generate `modality_missing` or `modality_ambiguous` questions, treat them as alternate evaluation views created later from the same complete conversation.
- For modality_missing items:
  - specify which modality is removed
  - do not invent a replacement cue, replacement voice_style, replacement wording, or alternate delivery description
  - the question must reason over the same underlying conversation content under a reduced-observation condition only
- For modality_ambiguous items:
  - specify which modality is weak, noisy, or unclear
  - ambiguity means the original modality cue becomes unreliable, blurry, weak, or hard to interpret
  - do not replace the original cue with a new concrete cue such as a different tone description
- If a turn has voice_style metadata, questions may rely on that observable delivery description; do not assume a real audio file exists unless audio_id is present and modality_available includes "audio".
- For `pseudo_conflict` adversarial items:
  - create the conflict from a plausible but incomplete reading of turns that already exist in the conversation
  - do not add hypothetical prior statements, fabricated memories, or counterfactual dialogue content that is not present in the source conversation
  - the adversarial twist must come from misreading, over-weighting, or under-weighting existing evidence, not from injecting new facts into the prompt

